00:51:42,320 --> 00:51:44,199
Here we go.

1011
00:51:44,200 --> 00:51:45,799
Come on, the Celica.
Don't let me down.

1012
00:51:45,800 --> 00:51:50,120
Best of luck, Fred.
Three, two, one, go!

1013
00:51:55,520 --> 00:51:58,119
Well, it's a keen start.
Come on, the Celica!

1014
00:51:58,120 --> 00:51:59,479
I like this. This works well.

1015
00:51:59,480 --> 00:52:00,919
It's lovely.
It's brilliant.

1016
00:52:00,920 --> 00:52:03,560
It's like a computer game.
Wzz-vroom! It's like Fred-vision.

1017
00:52:04,920 --> 00:52:07,240
Ooh, that was
a bit close to them cars.

1018
00:52:08,840 --> 00:52:10,320
This is The Stig.

1019
00:52:12,680 --> 00:52:13,719
I think he might have him,

1020
00:52:13,720 --> 00:52:15,919
cos I think that is a heavy
old boat, that estate car.

1021
00:52:15,920 --> 00:52:17,439
A bit of a bump. Wahey!

1022
00:52:17,440 --> 00:52:19,319
Here we are.
Come on. Go, go, go.

1023
00:52:19,320 --> 00:52:21,719
He's ahead, isn't he?
Ooh.

1024
00:52:21,720 --> 00:52:24,559
Last lap, Fred. Last lap. Keep
pushing, son! Keep pushing!

1025
00:52:24,560 --> 00:52:26,760
Come on, the Celica!
Get round.

1026
00:52:32,400 --> 00:52:34,239
That was close.
Keep going, Fred!

1027
00:52:34,240 --> 00:52:37,439
You're doing a great job!
Oh, I missed it!

1028
00:52:37,440 --> 00:52:39,599
I think he's just overshot it
and gone straight on.

1029
00:52:39,600 --> 00:52:41,999
I missed it.
I was daydreaming!

1030
00:52:42,000 --> 00:52:43,120
OK, so we're done.

1031
00:52:46,240 --> 00:52:47,799
HE LAUGHS

1032
00:52:47,800 --> 00:52:49,519
He's definitely behind...

1033
00:52:49,520 --> 00:52:51,360
I think the old GPS failed!

1034
00:52:54,320 --> 00:52:56,960
No! It was going so well.

1035
00:53:01,880 --> 00:53:03,919
Here he comes.

1036
00:53:03,920 --> 00:53:06,760
Oh, no, no, no, no, no, no.

1037
00:53:08,520 --> 00:53:12,439
Jeez! One mistake cost me.

1038
00:53:12,440 --> 00:53:15,399
How are we gonna play this?
Do the applause thingy.

1039
00:53:15,400 --> 00:53:16,920
BOTH CHEER

1040
00:53:19,480 --> 00:53:20,879
Fantastic!
All in one piece.

1041
00:53:20,880 --> 00:53:22,599
Fantastic!
Well done, Andrew.

1042
00:53:22,600 --> 00:53:24,479
Fantastic!
That was amazing!

1043
00:53:24,480 --> 00:53:26,359
Thank you for
your patronising tones.

1044
00:53:26,360 --> 00:53:27,719
PADDY AND CHRIS LAUGH

1045
00:53:27,720 --> 00:53:29,519
Did you see The Stig
actually behind you?

1046
00:53:29,520 --> 00:53:33,079
I just lost me bearings.
I was going straight.

1047
00:53:33,080 --> 00:53:35,199
The Celica
is in one piece.

1048
00:53:35,200 --> 00:53:37,359
And, more importantly,
so is he.

1049
00:53:37,360 --> 00:53:39,359
And we're only 2-0 down.
Thanks, Pad.

1050
00:53:39,360 --> 00:53:41,999
So... Oh, that's two cars
crushed.

1051
00:53:42,000 --> 00:53:43,279
On you go.

1052
00:53:43,280 --> 00:53:44,719
Oh. Go get 'em, tiger.

1053
00:53:44,720 --> 00:53:47,399
Got to do it for the Civic.
Got to do it for the Civic!

1054
00:53:47,400 --> 00:53:49,879
Yeah, that's three cars
crushed.

1055
00:53:49,880 --> 00:53:51,599
CHRIS LAUGHS

1056
00:53:51,600 --> 00:53:54,199
So, with Fred's Celica

1057
00:53:54,200 --> 00:53:56,040
now off to the great track day
in the sky...

1058
00:53:57,360 --> 00:53:58,599
..trying to stop the crusher

1059
00:53:58,600 --> 00:54:02,479
from enjoying
a full three-course supper...

1060
00:54:02,480 --> 00:54:05,359
..would be McGuinness
and his Civic.

1061
00:54:05,360 --> 00:54:10,479
And in a clear statement
of contempt for his chances,

1062
00:54:10,480 --> 00:54:15,239
Stig had decided to take him
on in the Vauxhall Agila.

1063
00:54:15,240 --> 00:54:17,199
Paddy, we need you here.

1064
00:54:17,200 --> 00:54:21,400
Leave it to the gaffer, boys.
Oh, here we go.

1065
00:54:25,520 --> 00:54:26,839
Are you ready, Pad?

1066
00:54:26,840 --> 00:54:31,519
In three, two, one, go!

1067
00:54:31,520 --> 00:54:34,519
Go, Paddy. Go on, son!

1068
00:54:34,520 --> 00:54:36,200
We're off.

1069
00:54:38,080 --> 00:54:39,519
Oh, 'ey up.
This is a bit tricky.

1070
00:54:39,520 --> 00:54:42,239
'Ey up. There we go. Wahey!

1071
00:54:42,240 --> 00:54:44,640
Stig's got his eye in now. Look at
the speed he's going at here.

1072
00:54:47,760 --> 00:54:51,120
There we go. Hey-hey!
He looks a bit slow.

1073
00:54:52,640 --> 00:54:54,279
The Stig's round here now.

1074
00:54:54,280 --> 00:54:55,679
Is he ahead?
Comfortably.

1075
00:54:55,680 --> 00:54:57,319
Oh, he's killing him.
He's killing him.

1076
00:54:57,320 --> 00:54:59,679
Oh, my Lord.
Come on, Pad.

1077
00:54:59,680 --> 00:55:00,999
Man alive!

1078
00:55:01,000 --> 00:55:04,039
Over the line. Over the line!
Keep going. Come on, Pad!

1079
00:55:04,040 --> 00:55:05,959
That's one.
He's nowhere near.

1080
00:55:05,960 --> 00:55:07,320
BOTH LAUGH

1081
00:55:08,320 --> 00:55:09,880
Come on.

1082
00:55:12,040 --> 00:55:12,960
Where's The Stig?

1083
00:55:15,280 --> 00:55:17,319
What's McGuinness playing at?
He's here again, the Stig.

1084
00:55:17,320 --> 00:55:18,839
Come on, Paddy!

1085
00:55:18,840 --> 00:55:21,439
Oh, God. Oh, God.
Come on, come on, Pad.

1086
00:55:21,440 --> 00:55:23,360
Argh! Come on.

1087
00:55:25,120 --> 00:55:26,640
Go! Go, go, go!

1088
00:55:27,800 --> 00:55:31,479
Oh, no. He's... Where is he?
Come on, Pad. Paddy!

1089
00:55:31,480 --> 00:55:33,439
There he goes.

1090
00:55:33,440 --> 00:55:34,719
Is that it?

1091
00:55:34,720 --> 00:55:36,719
FRED ON RADIO: Paddy,
you've finished. Come in.

1092
00:55:36,720 --> 00:55:37,760
Oh.

1093
00:55:38,880 --> 00:55:40,399
He's no idea. He's no idea.

1094
00:55:40,400 --> 00:55:41,959
Lost by about 200 metres.

1095
00:55:41,960 --> 00:55:43,359
BOTH LAUGH

1096
00:55:43,360 --> 00:55:46,439
Dear me. OK, ready? Ready?
Wait, wait, wait. Here we go.

1097
00:55:46,440 --> 00:55:47,799
Big applause.

1098
00:55:47,800 --> 00:55:50,639
CHRIS AND FRED CHEER

1099
00:55:50,640 --> 00:55:53,999
Go get in!
Go on, son!

1100
00:55:54,000 --> 00:55:55,559
Is it three for the scrapper??

1101
00:55:55,560 --> 00:55:57,159
BOTH LAUGH

1102
00:55:57,160 --> 00:56:00,519
Listen, you're too happy.
You're too happy.

1103
00:56:00,520 --> 00:56:03,559
I take it that's me.

1104
00:56:03,560 --> 00:56:05,319
You came second.

1105
00:56:05,320 --> 00:56:07,959
That's the way we look at it.
See? Positive.

1106
00:56:07,960 --> 00:56:10,920
Second place. Never mind.
So what does that mean?

1107
00:56:13,920 --> 00:56:16,759
Well, first of all,
it meant the crusher

1108
00:56:16,760 --> 00:56:18,839
had had a busy evening.

1109
00:56:18,840 --> 00:56:20,240
Oh!

1110
00:56:21,400 --> 00:56:22,999
Oh, no!

1111
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:24,399
No, no, no.

1112
00:56:24,400 --> 00:56:26,239
Oh...

1113
00:56:26,240 --> 00:56:27,600
Oh...

1114
00:56:28,880 --> 00:56:30,479
My word.

1115
00:56:30,480 --> 00:56:33,399
Me little Civic. Here it comes.

1116
00:56:33,400 --> 00:56:34,599
ALL GROAN

1117
00:56:34,600 --> 00:56:36,999
It's pooing out a Civic.

1118
00:56:37,000 --> 00:56:38,400
What a shame.

1119
00:56:41,840 --> 00:56:43,479
My gosh.

1120
00:56:43,480 --> 00:56:47,119
What's more,
it was time to conclude that,

1121
00:56:47,120 --> 00:56:49,999
while there may well be
a few diamonds out there

1122
00:56:50,000 --> 00:56:51,519
in the used-car rough...

1123
00:56:51,520 --> 00:56:52,880
Oh, dear.

1124
00:56:53,960 --> 00:56:57,039
..over the last couple
of days of intensive testing...

1125
00:56:57,040 --> 00:57:00,079
..we hadn't found them.

1126
00:57:00,080 --> 00:57:03,679
Well, our sub-Â£500 cars

1127
00:57:03,680 --> 00:57:06,399
reduced to furniture.

1128
00:57:06,400 --> 00:57:08,079
I've go to tell you, lads...

1129
00:57:08,080 --> 00:57:09,399
..I'm crushed!

1130
00:57:09,400 --> 00:57:12,720
I'm cru...! Come on,
let's get a cup of tea.

1131
00:57:14,840 --> 00:57:17,319
CHEERING AND APPLAUSE

1132
00:57:17,320 --> 00:57:19,440
No, I'm not sure about that.

1133
00:57:21,080 --> 00:57:23,919
So, the question was...

1134
00:57:23,920 --> 00:57:26,999
..for less than 500 quid,
could you get something

1135
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:29,479
that will give you years
of reliable motoring?

1136
00:57:29,480 --> 00:57:32,759
And the answer is yes -
well, as long as you don't go

1137
00:57:32,760 --> 00:57:35,879
ragging it round
a tank assault course

1138
00:57:35,880 --> 00:57:37,879
or race The Stig through
a deserted scrapyard.

1139
00:57:37,880 --> 00:57:40,359
I thought it was horrible,
watching 'em get scrapped.

1140
00:57:40,360 --> 00:57:42,319
That big claw coming in...
It was medieval.

1141
00:57:42,320 --> 00:57:44,319
Hung, drawn and quartered.

1142
00:57:44,320 --> 00:57:45,679
It was like Mad Max meets

1143
00:57:45,680 --> 00:57:47,959
that grabby machine thing you play
with down in the arcade.

1144
00:57:47,960 --> 00:57:50,119
I hate to see a car die.
But we have to say,

1145
00:57:50,120 --> 00:57:52,719
all these cars were going to the
scrapper anyhow, all right?

1146
00:57:52,720 --> 00:57:54,959
Exactly. If we hadn't
have bought 'em,

1147
00:57:54,960 --> 00:57:58,639
the breakers would have. They
died so others could live.

1148
00:57:58,640 --> 00:58:00,119
And at least we gave 'em
a bit of excitement

1149
00:58:00,120 --> 00:58:01,879
before they finally kicked
the bucket.

1150
00:58:01,880 --> 00:58:03,039
And look at this -

1151
00:58:03,040 --> 00:58:06,519
we've got three beautiful
coffee tables, hey?

1152
00:58:06,520 --> 00:58:08,359
CHEERING AND APPLAUSE
Ah!

1153
00:58:08,360 --> 00:58:10,319
That's the end of the show
for tonight.

1154
00:58:10,320 --> 00:58:11,799
We'll be back next week,

1155
00:58:11,800 --> 00:58:13,679
when we're letting
Chris Harris loose

1156
00:58:13,680 --> 00:58:15,399
in an actual World Rally car.

1157
00:58:15,400 --> 00:58:17,199
CHEERING

1158
00:58:17,200 --> 00:58:19,519
And we're gonna
go back in time

1159
00:58:19,520 --> 00:58:23,119
to tackle motorsport
1920s-style.

1160
00:58:23,120 --> 00:58:24,439
See you then. Goodnight.

1161
00:58:24,440 --> 00:58:26,200
CHEERING AND APPLAUSE

